**NOTES**

1. I wrote this guide with a lot of details since people have varying knowledge of tech, so sorry if some of it seems obvious.  
     
2. Every Splash and every Splash Director is different\! While this guide will hopefully help in answering many Splash-related questions, there is no single way to plan a Splash, so if you disagree with a policy or practice in this guide, or find a better way of doing things, then do it\! Just check with your co-director and mentor first, since many of these policies have evolved over a number of Splashes.

# S1: Introductory Materials {#s1:-introductory-materials}

## S1.01 Responsibilities of Directors & Mentors {#s1.01-responsibilities-of-directors-&-mentors}

Congratulations on becoming a Splash director\!

### Directors’ responsibilities:  {#directors’-responsibilities:}

As director, you are responsible for making sure the program runs smoothly. This means making sure that everything that needs to get done does get done, and as a result, delegation of tasks will be a very important part of your duties. If things don’t get done and someone has to stay up all night the day before Splash, that will mean you and your co-director. Your mentor is responsible for helping you and teaching you everything you need to know in order to run a Splash (and for making sure you stay on the right track), but at the end of the day, you are responsible for the program’s success.

A (by no means comprehensive) list of very general directors tasks is below:

- Checking the Splash email daily (and at least twice a day closer to the program date) and respond to emails appropriately (this document includes a number of sample email situations you should familiarize yourself with)  
- Meeting weekly with your co-director for \~2+ hours (meetings tend to run a bit longer during busy weeks) to create an agenda and start doing trickier tasks  
- Make Splash announcements and assign tasks during weekly team meetings; this also means missing as few weekly team meetings as possible; ideally this number should be 0, but missing 1-2 meetings for legitimate reasons (for the entire semester) is normally okay if you plan ahead and make sure that your co-director can attend  
- Basically all logistical details aside from the reservation of the major rooms are your responsibility (more details are provided later in the document, of course). Also, do not assume that assigning a task to someone means that they have completed it. You need to confirm that any assigned task has actually been done (and done in the correct manner).  
- Double-checking to catch errors made by admin team members that are relevant to the program

### What does my mentor do? {#what-does-my-mentor-do?}

Your mentor is there to teach you how to do Splash-related tasks that you may have trouble with, and to generally be your go-to person for any questions (BUT you should always check this document before asking your mentor questions, because a simple Control F search of this document can provide the answer to many questions). Additionally, your mentor will check up on how things are going throughout the semester. Mentors do not usually attend directors meetings with the following exceptions: part of the 1st meeting to help get things started; the meeting(s) for scheduling classes; the meeting when student registration opens; and the last meeting before Splash happens. Mentors are not there to fill in for the directors, but rather to help make sure the directors are staying on track for a successful Splash.

## S1.02 Splash Data to Know {#s1.02-splash-data-to-know}

Below is Splash data that is useful to consider when trying to figure out how many people attend Splash, how many teachers teach, what yield is etc…

Some important things to note:

* The grade breakdown of students that attend Splash (see graph below)--this is super important because it shows us that we need a lot of classes for middle schoolers, but that any class taught only for 12 grade will be very unpopular.  
* The “Number of Class Hours (Capacity)” refers to the sum of Class Size Capacity\*Length of the Class\*Number of Sections for all classes that are registered; this is the most important metric for teacher registration because it tells you the capacity of students that can attend (the Number of Class Hours (filled) refers to how many of those hours were filled up; this is always much lower in part due to the fact that Number of Class Hours (Capacity) doesn’t account for the fact that we don’t always have enough large lecture halls to hold the maximum number of students that could potentially attend and also due to our yield)

Another note: Fall 18 was a smaller Splash in terms of attendance, even though the \# of preregistered students was around the average. It was a rainy day, which often means low yield.

## S1.04 Intro to emails {#s1.04-intro-to-emails}

### Checking the gmail {#checking-the-gmail}

You and your co-director will need to set up a plan for who will respond to which emails. Some directors trade off who is in charge of responding to email every day, while others have one director check in the morning and the other in the afternoon. Either way is fine, as long as emails are responded to in a timely manner. Additionally, checking the gmail and responding to emails is a task that should be evenly split between the directors, so if one system isn’t working out, then feel free to switch how emails are divided. All emails should be responded to within a day, and during times like teacher and student registration start/end and during the week before the program, the gmail should be checked as much as possible so that time-sensitive matters are resolved (there are inevitably issues where people are having technical glitches that may or may not be our fault). If you are unsure of our policy on something when responding to an email, first check this document, then, if you are still unclear, ask your mentor about it.

### Sending emails {#sending-emails}

For important emails (ie. those being sent to more than 10 people or those responding to a sensitive subject matter), it is always a good idea to have your co-director proof-read your emails. Sending out incorrect information leads to many confused and upset parents, and can also make the day-of more difficult (ie. if school groups show up to the wrong location). Additionally, if you are sent an email that is of importance to the program (ie. a school group cancels last minute), you should be sure to let your co-director know to avoid confusion.

### Clearing the inbox: Archiving and folders {#clearing-the-inbox:-archiving-and-folders}

The email inbox should be empty at all times. This means dealing with the emails in the appropriate manner. There should **never** be opened emails that remain sitting in the inbox unless you have typed up a draft of the response and are waiting for a pending action to be completed (ie. obtaining info from someone about how to respond or having a co-director proofread the email).

There are 5 types of emails/ways to deal with an email:

1. If an email is clearly spam (we get a decent amount of spam) it should be archived.  
2. Emails you have to respond to and DO NOT contain info that you will need to refer back to frequently should be **archived**.  
3. The Splash email receives many emails about Sprout. These should be forwarded to yalesprout@gmail.com when they are received.   
4. Some of the emails in the drive will also be meant for the Splash Presidents (it is usually fairly obvious which emails they are—they are usually about website things or finances). These should be left in the inbox as unread (change the email status to “unread” if you accidentally click on it) so that the Presidents know they have to respond to it. If any of these emails stay in the inbox for multiple days, Slack the Presidents to make sure they are aware of the email/don’t expect the directors to handle the matter.  
5. If the email is something you will have to refer back to later (ie. school group emails, teacher material requests, teacher materials reimbursements, teacher forms, confirmations from the professors teaching at parent program, and anything else that seems important), then it should be placed into the appropriate folder after it is responded to. This makes life way wayyy easier than trying to dig up old emails.

To make this last step easier, at the start of the year you should make the following folders:

Note: As the program goes on, definitely add more folders as needed\!  
   
1\.     Spring 20: School Groups  
2\.     Spring 20: Parent Program Confirmations  
3\.     Spring 20: Teacher Material Requests  
4\.     Spring 20: Teacher Material Reimbursements  
5\.     Spring 20: Teacher Forms

Email Logistics:  
It is a good idea to add the Splash gmail to your phone as you will be using it quite a bit. Also, as the program approaches, I highly suggest you keep a tab on your browser that always has the gmail open, this way you are sure to remember to check it and respond quickly.

### Mail Merge {#mail-merge}

Directors should download the Chrome webapp [“Streak” (click here to go to the chrome web store)](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/streak-crm-for-gmail/pnnfemgpilpdaojpnkjdgfgbnnjojfik) which allows you to send mass emails. While most of the emails will get sent through the website, Streak will allow you to use mail merge (it extracts emails from a .csv file, which is an export format in excel) so you can contact lists of people (ie. one email we send is to all the DUS’s). The basic steps of using Streak to send a message are:

1. Download Streak and log into Streak using the Splash gmail; give it the permissions it asks for.  
2. Generate an excel file that has the emails of all the people you want to email. If you are copying emails in from the Splash website using the “generate a list” function (see the section below that discusses how to get these into a format that works with mail merge). If you want to make the emails more personal, you can add the name of the person next to the their email (in a separate column) as well, and Streak can automatically extract these names and their associated emails/info.  
3. Delete all information on the excel sheet aside from the emails and the names (and headers for the columns). The sheet should look like this:  
   ![][image2]  
4. On excel, go to File\>Save As and save as a .csv file. This is the only file type Streak accepts.  
5. Click compose like you normally would. In the top right corner next to the Cc and Bc buttons, you will see “Mail Merge” in light grey font. Click on that.  
6. An email should open up; in the box at the top, click the blue text saying “Upload .csv” and choose the .csv file appropriately.  
7. Streak will tell you the number of recipients it has found at the top of the email, and lists their names on the right. Double check these (briefly).  
8. If desired, insert a variable, such as the recipients name. To do this, click on the “insert variable” button (see below). Be sure to include Mr./Ms./Professor if appropriate.  
   ![][image3]  
   

### Website Emails {#website-emails}

Generally, it is easier to send emails through the website than through gmail, but there is also a greater chance of having the email being caught by a spam filter when you send emails from the website. The first emails you send will likely be teacher recruitment emails, and you should check to see if those emails are caught by peoples’ spam filters by testing them with admins and yourself (see Avoiding Spam Filters 101 below).

Steps to sending a website email:

1. Go to Manage\>Your Program’s Name\>Email  
2. (a) Use either a Basic List (which can choose basic categories, ie. all students on financial aid) or a Combination list (which can choose complex categories, ie. all parents of students that haven’t paid or submitted financial aid but have signed up for a class)  
   (b) If you’re using a combination list, for example the one listed in parenthesis above, you would start by selecting “Students who signed up for at least one class” in the dropdown menu. Then you would unselect “email the students” and you would instead select “email the students’ guardians.” Then you would select the “AND” and  “NOT” boxes next to “Students who have filled out the credit card form” and “Students who have been granted financial aid” (note that financial aid would have to be updated before you could do this). If needed, you can also add filters using the button on the bottom (this can also be used for generating arbitrary user lists).  
3. Check to make sure the number of users you selected fits what you would expect (it will tell you the number of users at the top)  
4. In the “From” box, type in “yalesplash@gmail.com” (without the quotes). This address will autoforward to the Splash gmail, and it helps avoid spam filters. The “Reply to” box can be left blank  
5. Follow the steps in the “Avoiding Spam Filters 101” below  
6. To add a hyperlink, click on the little chain link thingy (also, usually you will want the link to open in a separate tab, so you should check that box).  
   ![][image4]  
7. ALWAYS double check the text of the email in the “Preview” feature AND make sure DOUBLE CHECK ALL LINKS, even if you already checked them when drafting the email (sometimes HTML is whacky and when you paste in hyperlinks, they get messed up).

2. Include the Splash footer (provided in the example below) which has the **street address of LOM**, as well as an **unsubscribe button**

### Arbitrary User Lists {#arbitrary-user-lists}

1. You will need to use arbitrary user lists to send emails through the gmail; these are often emails to small subsets of the Splash users.   
2. Go to “Manage” and then to your program page. Under “Generate Printables,” go to “Arbitrary User List”  
3. Only select that you want the names and emails, or emails alone  
4. Export to HTML and copy into excel (I’m pretty sure HTML is the better format to choose, but I’m not 100% so just try both the first time you do it)  
5. Use the “text to columns” feature in excel to get the proper format

## S1.05 Delegating Tasks {#s1.05-delegating-tasks}

Trying to assign people tasks during the middle of the semester when people are busy is much harder than assigning them responsibilities at the start of the semester--so definitely assign people to the following tasks at the start of the semester.

You can both decide which positions seem necessary to assign to others and which ones you will do on your own, but these are what I’d recommend. For Spring ‘19, we didn’t formally assign any of these positions, which led to us doing most of the work… so ultimately assigning these tasks will reduce your workload.

1. Teacher Recruitment Czar   
   For Fall ‘19, this will be Ananya; this task involves probably the most work because teacher recruitment is always a challenge. Directors are ultimately responsible for ensuring that teacher recruitment happens, and for working directly with this person to coordinate what needs to get done. Some of this job will likely end up being shared by the directors just because it can be so time consuming/difficult.

2. Class Approvals, Teacher forms, and Materials Request Czar  
   This task should be shared by the directors but parts of it can be doled out to admins to reduce the workload; ultimately though, it is important that both directors have an idea of all the classes being taught, for two reasons (1) this makes it easiest to resolve problems on the day-of (2) directors **need** to be aware of special room requirements for scheduling purposes. This role consists of approving classes and noting down materials requests/other notable things (ie. if a class needs the computer lab, a kitchen, or is meeting in a classroom and then leaving for some other location). It also consists of keeping track of teacher forms and approving/not approving materials requests. All of the work done by admins for this task should be checked by the directors.  
     
3. School Groups Czar  
   This person will have little to do until student registration opens; this task is also a significant responsibility though, later on. Basically this person has to email all the school groups continually and check their forms over, etc. This is another job where director oversight is key.  
     
4. Financial Aid & Payment Approval Czar  
   This task is probably the least time consuming, and likely amounts to 4 hours of work or so over a two week period. This task is also easily learned, but is important. This task consists of updating the financial aid and sending payment reminders every 3 days over a two week period.  
 


5. Parent Program Czar  
   This person is in charge of planning the whole parent program. This actually doesn’t take that much time, and **should be done as soon as possible, meaning in the first 1-3 meetings.**

 

## S1.06 Weekly Directors’ Meetings {#s1.06-weekly-directors’-meetings}

Weekly directors meetings consist of:

1. Making the agenda (see S1.07 below)  
2. Resolving pressing emails that require the input of both directors  
3. Getting a jump on any director’s tasks; directors tasks should be things that are either (1) very important to be done in a timely/proper manner (2) would take just as long to explain to someone else as it would to do yourself (for example, in the vast majority of cases you shouldn’t be asking admins to respond to emails for you…)  
4. Assigning director’s tasks to one another

## S1.07 Making Agendas {#s1.07-making-agendas}

Making an agenda involves:

1. Looking at the Master Splash Timeline and copying over any relevant tasks  
2. Adding any tasks leftover from last week  
3. Determining which tasks can be completed by directors, and which tasks can be completed by the admin team; make clear sections for each (put directors tasks on a separate page below everything else)  
4. For certain tasks, it may be convenient to pre-assign an admin (ie. tasks relevant to a specific “Czar” (see section S1.05))  
5. Determining any relevant team announcements, and place them at the top of the agenda (ie. teacher reg opens today)  
6. Add any updates, for example the number of teachers you have and the number you still need  
7. Adding any tasks relevant to the whole team  
8. Determine if any Take-Home tasks will be necessary, and add them to the agenda  
9. Determine if there are enough tasks so that all admins will have something to do during the meeting; if this is not the case, go back to the Master Timeline and start pulling events from future weeks that can be done early. It is always better to have too many tasks rather than too few  
10. Feel free to do something similar to “Admin of the Week” or come up with your own ideas for fun icebreakers/agenda items, provided that they take up less than a few minutes of meeting time; these shouldn’t be full on games or anything that will be too distracting.

## S1.10 General Website Tips and Features {#s1.10-general-website-tips-and-features}

Make sure coordinates for Splash Headquarters are inputted correctly first\!\! If its not, tag settings won’t update.

### Finding a student account on the website {#finding-a-student-account-on-the-website}

1. This task is something you will actually spend a lot of time; there are often issues finding student accounts due to one of the following (1) Student has multiple accounts (2) Student forgot their username and provides only their name (3) Student registered under parent’s name (4) Student registered for the wrong type of account (ie. a parent account) (5) Student registered using different name or made a typo in their account name  
2. The steps to remedy these problems are fairly straight forward, but basically, you should:  
1) Start by searching the name provided  
2) If no name was provided, search the email address  
3) If the full name gives no results, try searching just their last name and scrolling through (do the same for the first name, too)  
4) Try searching their parent/guardian’s name  
5) Email the student/parent asking for a username  
6) One thing that happens sometimes is a school group will tell you a student is registered but you can’t find their account; one option for this is to use arbitrary user lists and filter by school (using only part of the school’s name to search)  
7) If you really can’t find the account, ask the student to make a new account

### Troubleshooting Student Errors {#troubleshooting-student-errors}

Very often, you will receive emails from parents/students complaining that some aspect of the website is not working. You should follow these steps or something similar to fix the issue:

1. Consider if the student should be able to do what they are trying to do (ie. if they are trying to pay for the program after the payment deadline, then they will obviously have trouble); this resolves a large chunk of the emails you will get  
2. Morph into the user and try and see if the error is reproducible  
3. Also test to see if the error is reproducible with the fake student account (there are a number of these, for example the account with username “fakestudent1” is a recent one that works)  
4. Try to pinpoint the cause of the error; for example, if the error is reproducible with the student account but not the fake student account, then there must be something weird in the student account that differs from the fake student account  
5. If it is reproducible and you don’t know how to fix it, contact others; if it isn’t reproducible then (a) give step by step instructions on how to perform the task and tell them that if they still are having difficulties we suggest the student/parent tries again after restarting their browser and clearing their cookies or using a different web browser (b) if needed, perform the task for the student (ie. if the student can’t order lunch, you can ask them what they want and do it for them; BUT, we try not to register students for classes on their behalf; this is because many classes fill quickly and it’s unfair to put kids into classes through our computers. The one exception to this is when we grant a student permission to take a higher level class (see Scenario 4 below))

### Adjusting account permissions {#adjusting-account-permissions}

Adjusting account permissions is useful in many scenarios, for example, if you want to test something with a fake student account, but registration isn’t open yet, you have to adjust the permissions of the fake student account to let them register early; **you should never** adjust the deadlines for Splash to achieve the same goal. Another example is when you want to let someone register late due to extenuating circumstances (ie. they tried to register at 4:59pm but the website crashed).

Find username of the account you’d like to give permissions

* Give this account permissions.  
  * Go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/users/permission/)  
  * Add a new permission, giving the user the needed permissions. **Do NOT fill out the role field.** If you put student there, anyone with the role of student will have those permissions. That is NOT what you want (this would be equivalent to changing something on the deadlines page).  
* If you added a fake student to the program, make sure to go and remove this fake student from your program. To do this, go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/program/studentregistration/) and search for the user. Select all the checkboxes relevant to your program, and press "expire student registrations". Also go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/accounting/transfer/), search for the user, select the checkboxes relevant to your program, and press "delete selected transfers."

### The “Transfers” section of the website {#the-“transfers”-section-of-the-website}

The [transfers section](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/accounting/transfer/) is one place to go if you want to quickly find out the following:

1. Has a student paid  
2. Is a student on financial aid  
3. Did a student order lunch  
4. Did a student order a shirt

Some notes about Transfers: 

1. It has information for **all** programs; be sure that you’re only looking at the info for your program\!  
2. If the “Source” column says “Grants” it means the student is on Financial aid

### Example emails and their responses {#example-emails-and-their-responses}

| Scenario 1: Parent thinks registration is open but it isn’t and is therefore claims they are having issues with registration |
| :---- |
| Times you might receive this: Anytime before student reg opens |
| Email: *“I am trying to register my son for Yale Splash but I am having trouble and none of the links on your website will let me register.”* |

### Grade change requests {#grade-change-requests}

You will sometimes receive emails that look like this:

| server@yale.learningu.org |  |  |  |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |

A grade change request was received from: Joshua Tochimani (ID: 22032, e-mail: joshuatoch95@gmail.com).

Current Grade: 8

Claimed Grade: 9

Reason: Miss clicked

Please review the request here: [http://yale.learningu.org/admin/users/gradechangerequest/243/](http://yale.learningu.org/admin/users/gradechangerequest/243/)

If this occurs, you should look at the reason, and if it seems legitimate, then approve the request. Occasionally, students will attempt to change their grade to try and get into a higher level class. While it’s impossible to tell for sure when this has happened, there are sometimes clues. For example, in Spring 19’, 3 kids from the same school all tried to change their grade from 8th to 9th because they had all “misclicked” within the span of 5 minutes. In those cases, you should send an email like the one below:

Hello,

We noticed that you submitted a grade change request from 8th to 9th grade. Please respond with evidence of your enrollment in 9th grade so that we can approve your request (this could be a class schedule or any other school-issued document that has your grade on it).

Thank you,

\-Splash Team

## S1.15: Admin schedule {#s1.15:-admin-schedule}

Tips for making admin schedule:  
Logistical tips:  
1\.     It’s surprisingly hard to keep the “Whole day schedule” consistent with the “Individual schedule” tab. To make this easier, do **all** the individual schedules first, and then add them into the “Whole day schedule” tab  
2\.     Use Command \+ Enter to make a new line in a cell (this prevents text from overflowing and being hidden  
   
Tips for assigning tasks:

1\.     Check with Presidents if any visiting admins or past admins will be attending (you can also reach out to past admins if you think they might be willing to help out/are in New Haven; especially do this if you are low on admins on the day-of); generally, try to assign visiting/former admins to tasks with current admins so there is someone who is aware of all the up-to-date policies with them

2\.     Be sure to double check which of your admins are teaching classes to avoid conflicts; admins usually won’t put this on the “admin conflicts” spreadsheet

3\.     A maximum of two people can be assigned to each tech support position (WLH and LC) because only two people can share a Google voice number. This means that a few people will be on a lot of tech support shifts

4\.     Assign tasks (in part) based on who was in charge of what pre-Splash tasks—in other words, the person who dealt with school groups should be at school group sign in. The person who dealt with teacher material request forms should be at teacher check-in (for at least some of the day)

5\.     Reserve a few of the experienced admins to be in charge of cleaning up sign-in, setting up lunch, and cleaning up lunch, since they will (hopefully) know where things should go

6\.     Keep in mind the experience level of the admin when assigning tasks and try to assign more logistically challenging tasks to experienced admins

7\.     Only assign tech support to people who feel comfortable doing it

8\.     There should (ideally) always be at least one experienced admin in LC

9\.     With the exception of sign-in, at least one director should be at the WLH admin desk for all of the shifts. During sign-in, an experienced admin (ideally your mentor) should be at admin desk

10\.  Make sure people know that during the last two blocks, it is implied that they will help clean up no matter what they are assigned to

11\.  See the Zipcar section for details about how to assign this person tasks

12\.  If you don’t have enough admins to fill all the slots on the schedule, ask your mentor which tasks to prioritize, and which ones can have fewer people. If you have extra admins (based on the template), then either put them on clean-up duty (there should be multiple people on clean-up/float duty whenever possible), or add them to LC/Parent program or another area that doesn’t have many people. Try to make sure the people on clean-up/float duty are people who will use that time productively to help the program rather than just hanging out in Teacher lounge or going somewhere else on campus (lol we have had that happen)

   
Teacher Policies:  
   
Non-Yale Teachers: Non-Yale students are welcome to teach classes, but they must be an undergraduate or graduate student at a university somewhere (the exception to this is past admins, who we also let teach). If the person lives far away, and/or asks for travel reimbursements, then be sure to check with the Presidents if we have the budget to allow that for that specific semester. Non-Yale teachers still have to attend teacher training **if** they haven’t taught for Yale Splash before; in this case, one of the directors should schedule a FaceTime or Google Hangouts call with them and briefly run through our policies—this may sound like a pain but it should only take 10 minutes or so (you can just go over the main points).

## S2.01: Advertising {#s2.01:-advertising}

The advertising should be partially taken on by the person assigned to this task at the start of the semester, but it is your job to make sure that you are actually getting enough teachers and to do many of the other advertising aspects, like sending emails and making FB posts, etc (you should find a way to divide this up). A few things to keep in mind:

1. Teacher recruitment events are usually poorly attended; either have one, and advertise really well, or don’t have one at all  
2. The vast majority of teachers won’t sign up until the last few days, so definitely advertise as much as possible, but don’t panic too much  
3. Facebook posts and emails should be sent with increasing frequency as the deadline nears--this means posting every day and emailing twice a day. Be sure to only email teachers that have not signed up for a class  
4. Raffling off Amazon gift cards doesn’t seem to help get more teachers; maybe something like giving free mugs to the first 20 teachers would help?  
5. Refer to the [Splash Data to Know](#s1.02-splash-data-to-know) section for info on how many teachers/class hours/classes/sections you should have

## S2.02: Approving Classes {#s2.02:-approving-classes}

Approving classes (Sourced from How-To’s folder):  
What to look for:

* Content  
  * Is it appropriate for the indicated grade range?  
    * Remember that we can’t guarantee the age of the students in their class, so it’s better to err on the side of caution  
  * Will it sustain an hour-long class? Are they trying to do too much?  
    * Usually most important for new teachers since returning teachers have a better sense of what it means to teach for an hour  
  * Do they intend to teach any of the no-no topics? (listed below)  
    * ACT/SAT prep  
    * Anything related to alcohol/bartending (21 \= CT legal drinking age, 18 \= CT legal bartending age)  
    * Sex-ed  
    * “How to get into college”  
      * This can be worked into a more acceptable class, e.g. “How to craft a resume” or “Writing a Personal Essay” could be good options to suggest depending on what they want to focus on.  
  * Do they want to teach about something that’s currently a contentious/divisive issue?  
    * e.g. Israel/Palestine relations  
* Length  
  * Give 2-hour classes extra scrutiny, since children have a much harder time focusing for 2 hours, and it’s often harder for teachers to plan to effectively use all of that 2-hour chunk of time. (They also make scheduling a pain.)  
    * Some classes, like art/music/theater/improv/dance workshops, science experiments, cooking classes (essentially something that’s very hands-on) work great as 2 hour classes  
* Location  
  * Do they have any specific location requests/requirements?  
    * Is it simple like “need a chalkboard” or “need a room with windows”?  
    * Or will they need to reserve a separate space? (e.g. dance studio, kitchen)  
* Budget (look in the comments/materials sections of the class submission)  
  * Did they ask for a reasonable amount of materials (both in price and amount)?  
  * Remember the $30 is a guideline amount, and if they have a compelling reason to spend more (e.g. art supplies, science equipment) presidents/directors can authorize an increased budget for the class.

What to do with any potential problems:

* Content  
  * Email the teacher **as soon as** the class is submitted and explain your concerns. This can take the form of a flat-out rejection, or you can ask questions or offer suggestions to refocus the direction of a class and confirm it will go well.  
  * Teachers are usually willing to work with us, and often appreciate suggestions about what has or has not worked well in the past (that can be an easy way to “refocus” a class to something you think will be more successful). This applies both to content itself and amount of content/time management.  
    * Mentors/organization leaders know which classes have been taught before and how successful they have been, so talk with them to see if the class has been taught before and has gone okay.  
  * If it’s a contentious topic, follow up to make sure the teacher is aware of potential issues and has plans for conflict resolution. Also confirm they’re presenting the matter as objectively as possible\!  
  * Continue following up/pestering teachers until you get responses and have worked out the problem. Remember that it’s your program, so you have the right to refuse a teacher that is unwilling to work with you to make sure the class is appropriate/well-planned.  
* Length  
  * If concerned about a 2-hour class: Explain our concerns with 2-hour classes, and ask if the teacher would be willing to teach a 1-hour class, at least the first time (if it’s a new class) so they can get a better sense of timing before deciding if it’s necessary to lengthen it. If the teacher really wants a 2-hour class we don’t usually fight them, just make sure to emphasize the extra planning that is necessary.  
  * We only suggest increasing the length of a class to 2 hours if they’re doing hands-on experiments or projects, or if they’re planning on traveling from the classroom to another location (see below). Otherwise, suggest that they simplify their lesson plan to better fit in an hour.  
  * Classes that travel from the original classroom to another space (e.g. Bass computer lab, dance studio, kitchen) should be 2 hours long. Walking to/from the other space and getting set up takes time, and there’s just not enough time in a 1-hour class to do that and also teach a full class.  
* Location  
  * Email the teacher **as soon as** you see their class submission to ensure there is enough time to reserve additional spaces.  
  * They should reserve the space themselves whenever possible. If they don’t have access to one of the nearby residential colleges (Silliman, Hopper, Berkeley) tell them we can reserve the space for them since we have admins in those colleges.  
* Budget  
  * Explain any concerns to the teachers and ask if there are ways they can redesign their class to not require those materials.  
  * For science classes, suggest they ask if they can borrow equipment/materials from departments or labs on campus.  
  * Like location reservations, it should be the teacher’s responsibility as much as possible to secure their materials.

   
If a teacher signs up for a **single** section of a class, **DO NOT** approve their class because we want to ask them to teach multiple sections and/or teach a class for 7-8th graders (middle school classes are highest in demand but lowest in supply, usually). Email them asking them to teach either (1) a middle school section (2) another middle school section.

If a teacher signs up for a class with a grade range 7-12 and **is a new teacher**, email them asking them to teach one 7-8 class and another 9-12 class, because classes with a wide age range can be harder to handle. If the teacher is experienced, we usually let this rule slide, but you should still ask them to teach more than 1 section if they aren’t.

Make a spreadsheet for **special requests/class notes.**

Do not approve a class with more than 2 sections for the same grade range. If the class size is small and the class seems like it will be very popular, exceptions can be made if it seems like the class will fill.

# S3: Post-Teacher Reg {#s3:-post-teacher-reg}

##  S3.01: Scheduling {#s3.01:-scheduling}

Scheduling must be completed after teacher reg has closed but AT LEAST 36 hours before student reg opens. This is because the course catalog must be emailed to students 24 hours before student reg opens, and the website takes many hours to send mass emails. The time that it takes to schedule varies based on how on top of things the people approving classes have been, but it usually takes **4-6 hours** (this is not an exaggeration) because it is a very complex process. A room should be reserved the week prior so that this can occur. The “Tips for Scheduling” below is **REQUIRED reading** before coming to scheduling.

Tips for scheduling

* **SCHEDULE 1 SECTION OF EACH CLASS FIRST, THEN GO BACK AND SCHEDULE THE SECOND SECTION, AND SO ON.**  
* **FOR PROGRAMS IN LC AND WLH, KEEP ALL MIDDLE SCHOOL CLASSES IN WLH\!**  
* **ALSO, PAY ATTENTION TO ANY SPECIAL REQUESTS TEACHERS HAVE FOR ROOM RESOURCES (e.g. PIANO, MOVABLE CHAIRS, etc). (This is why we had you make that spreadsheet of special requests/class notes when approving classes.)**  
* **The main goals are:**  
  * **Balance total class capacities, number of classes, number of classes per category, and number of classes (and overall capacity) per grade for each block.**  
  * **Note: usually it is hardest to get teachers for the 1st block, so as a rule of thumb, if a teacher has availability for 1st block, try to schedule them there\!**  
  * **Maximize the number of classes you are able to schedule (more spots for kids\!), while not scheduling more sections than there will be kids (empty classes and sad teachers).**  
  * **Match class size to room size as closely as possible (and if possible, put a class in a room that’s too big, not one that’s too small).**


1. Go to this doc and [Make sure room availabilities are set up correctly.](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1hzn4h0qy_eg6uNIeOYFcnBRyc_em4iuFW1RKTODPeQM/edit) This is really important\!  
2. Filter by class size to get the people who selected 200 as their capacity. There will be more of these than class blocks, so you will have to choose which ones get Sudler (and the large LC lecture halls if using). Any class in Sudler/large lecture halls should include 7-8 graders. Ideally, it should be 7-12. Also, if this class has been taught in the past, check if it filled the capacity of the room it was in last time. If not, it should not be in Sudler. I would advise against placing 2 sections of a class in Sudler.  
3. The ones that didn't get into Sudler but seem as though they might be popular and include middle schoolers should go into the WLH rooms with capacity 110 and 75, and the other similarly-large LC rooms. Filter to get the classes with capacity above 74 and see if any of these deserve those rooms either. Again, try to put classes accessible to middle schoolers in these rooms.  
4. Next, filter to get the smallest classes (below 25\) and schedule the ones for *middle schoolers*. Try to match capacity with room size as accurately as possible. Spread these tiny classes out amongst different time blocks.   
5. Next, open the dashboard and click the "timeslots" button. This will show you how well/badly you have done distributing middle school capacity across the blocks. Now schedule the remaining middle school classes while trying to put slightly larger classes in the timeslots with less capacity, and the smaller ones in the timeslots with higher capacity. Beware that these timeslots don’t update very well. The link noted below has useful info that does update regularly.  
6. Look at this page: [https://yale.learningu.org/manage/Splash/2022\_Spring/scheduling\_checks](https://yale.learningu.org/manage/Splash/2019_Fall/scheduling_checks) and click on "number of classes in each block by category". Make sure that the categories are evenly represented across blocks for middle schoolers.  
7. Now that you're done scheduling middle school classes, check in to see how the admin situation is looking. Write down which admins you currently have scheduled in each block. Note that you **shouldn’t really have admins teaching 1st block or block right before lunch** or your life will suck. You also shouldn’t have more than \~3-4 admins teaching per block. It’s easiest to schedule admins in 2nd block or 5th block, so put all/most of them there.  
8. Now schedule the rest of the admin classes.  
9. Now schedule the remaining classes (this should be high school classes and not admin classes). Keep a constant eye on the timeslot bottleneck situation and aim to make it as even as possible.  
10. Check the categories per time block again. Make sure it's even.  
11. Now that you're done, see how much the class capacities differ than room capacities. If the room capacity is greater than the class capacity by 5 or less, change the class capacity to match. If the room capacity is greater by more than 5, email the teacher saying their room allows more students and you'd love to give more students the chance to take their class, so would they be willing to increase class size to match room size (tell them this number). Wait for answers, and change accordingly.

# S4: Student Registration {#s4:-student-registration}

## S4.01 Testing Student Reg {#s4.01-testing-student-reg}

Before you test, the following things need to be done:

* [Line items](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/accounting/lineitemtype/) need to be added for your program for lunch and shirts.  
  * For Sprout, you will need 3 line items for lunch: "Lunch week 1", "Lunch week 2", "Lunch week 3". Splash just needs one.  
  * Lunch should look something like this, with as many options as choices you have for lunch:  
  * ![][image6]  
  * Shirts should look similar, but the amount dec should be 10.00, and the options should be S (adult), M (adult), L (adult), XL (adult).  
    * If you don’t specify adult sizes, people might assume kids’ sizes and the sizes will be icky.  
* **DO NOT DO THE FOLLOWING STEP WHILE AN EMAIL IS SENDING ON WEBSITE.**  
  To check if an email is sending, go to the back end and “email texts”. If the top item doesn’t have a send time in the right most column (if it says “none” or is blank), you cannot create a custom form (the website will shut down).  
* You need to create the custom form for your program and link it to student registration. This asks about what they're excited about and their allergies. It's important especially to see if a school teacher mass registered all their students, because in that case the responses would all be the same. Editing custom forms is hard.  
  * Go to this [link](https://yale.learningu.org/customforms/), and click on "create" near the top.  
  * Go down to "Create from an existing form" and choose the most recent form relevant to Sprout/Splash.  
  * Change the name field to match your program semester/year.  
  * Go to the links tab and change it so that it links to your program.  
  * Submit the form and hope for the best.  
  * Next, click on "Fill" next to your program's form at the same link.   
  * Look at the URL of the form that appeared. It should be something like: "[https://yale.learningu.org/customforms/view/97/](https://yale.learningu.org/customforms/view/97/)"  
  * Memorize that number at the end of the URL. In this case, 97\.  
  * Go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/customforms/form/), and click on your form. Memorize the link ID \#.  
  * Next, go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/tagdict/tag/). Create a new tag and make it look like this, but put that number you memorized in the value field and the link ID \# in the Object id field. Title it "learn\_extraform\_id" just like here, and have the content type be "program", just like shown:  
    ![][image7]  
  * Keep hoping for the best, but you should be good now.

Okay. So you have maybe completed the necessary prerequisites to student registration. 

* Check your deadlines and make sure students will have access at the correct time and it will end at the correct time.  
* Make sure the separate deadlines for registration mainpage & confirm reg are open until the end of your program date, and that credit card payment, and financial aid are open for a day or two beyond the end of student registration.

Find a fake student's account whose grade is in the right range. For example, "ktest".

* Give this account permissions.  
  * Go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/users/permission/)  
  * Add a new permission, giving the user all student permissions for the program for a certain amount of time. **Do NOT fill out the role field.** If you put student there, anyone with the role of student will have those permissions. That is NOT what you want (this would be equivalent to changing something on the deadlines page).  
* Search for the user on the main website and morph into them. Go to your student reg link, and check that you can fill out the form, make lunch and shirt purchases, and register for classes.  
  * Weird things that might come up:  
    * Is lunch a block that you can sign up for?  
    * Do all the blocks exist…  
* Once you are done, make sure to go and remove this fake student from your program. To do this, go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/program/studentregistration/) and search for the user. Select all the checkboxes relevant to your program, and press "expire student registrations". Also go [here](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/accounting/transfer/), search for the user, select the checkboxes relevant to your program, and press "delete selected transfers."

## S4.02 Day-of Student Reg Opening {#s4.02-day-of-student-reg-opening}

When student reg opens, you should expect to spend about 4 hours answering emails. Inevitably the website becomes extremely slow, and you will not be able to access any features. If you tested student reg, there shouldn’t be any major technical glitches. Despite this numerous parents will send emails claiming that the website is broken. You should be coordinating with your co-director about who will be answering which emails, and addressing issues that arise with your mentor, if they are not easily solved. A few policies to keep in mind:

* Even if parents/kids complain that they waited an hour for the website to load and now their favorite class has no spots left, you should not put them into the class  
* Parents/kids will oftentimes say that the website won’t load and ask us to register for them. Do not do this--reply and say that the student has to register.  
* As appropriate, emphasize that students (not parents) should be the ones signing up for classes

## S4.03 Student Payment {#s4.03-student-payment}

### Granting Financial Aid Requests {#granting-financial-aid-requests}

You should grant financial aid requests in chunks so that students know that they have received financial aid before the student payment deadline. You also have to grant financial aid in chunks because in order to send payment reminder emails to only the people that haven’t been granted financial (and also not to the people that have already paid), financial aid should be updated. Financial aid should therefore be granted about every 3 days--the same frequency as the payment reminders-- throughout the period after student reg opens and after the student payment/finaid deadlines. 

**NOTE--**there is probably a better way to do this; this is just the solution I found last year, but if you guys can find a better way, then do it\!

Steps to granting financial aid:

1. Open “[Administration Pages](https://yale.learningu.org/admin/)”  
2. Open “Financial Aid Requests” (This is NOT the same as “Financial Aid Grants”)  
3. Look in the “Program” column for the first one that says your program names and start from there  
4. (a) If the student is on Free/Reduced School Lunch (as indicated by a green check mark), their request will be automatically approved, as indicated by the “True” in the “Approved” column.  
   (b) If there is not a green check mark and is instead a red circle, you must now check to see if they’ve written anything in the “Household income” and “Please describe your situation.”  
   (c) If they have written nothing in these columns, then “(none)” will appear. If there is absolutely nothing written in either box, then we assume that the student did not intentionally apply for financial aid, and accidentally just clicked on the tab. This happens A LOT, so don’t be surprised.  
   (d) If the student has written literally anything in EITHER box (ie. its fine if they didn’t fill out their income or if they didn’t provide a reason), even if it’s just “Please grant my financial aid,” then we will grant them financial aid.  
   (e) To grant a student financial aid, click on their username. Under the Percent box of the “Financial aid grant” chart, type in “100” (without the “” marks). Then click “Save” in the bottom right hand corner.  
   (f) Repeat these steps for all students.  
   5\. Now, go back to the Administration Pages, and click on “Financial Aid Grants” (at the top of the page). You must now finalize the financial aid grants. You can do this all at once, so simply click on the checkbox next to the user ID of each student whose financial aid you want to approve. Once you have done this, click on the white box at the bottom of the page on the back “Footer” bar, and choose “Finalize Finaid grants” in the dropdown menu.  
   ![][image8]  
6. Now that the grants are finalized, you have to send emails to all the students telling them that they received financial aid. However, since you will be granting financial aid progressively (ie. you won’t do it all at once, but instead in chunks), you don’t want to send people multiple emails about being approved for financial aid. To avoid this, take the following steps:  
   	IMPORTANT NOTE: If this is the first time during the program you are granting financial aid, you can just follow step 12 and then copy and paste the email addresses into the email provided in 15/16.  
7. First make a copy of [this spreadsheet](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1xGWnJp_bF2eqguzHLUV6XSgO9bbwhRAk4iY4yDNIJbs/edit?usp=sharing) for your program. DO NOT just use this template version.  
8. Delete all the info in the username column and delete the data in the columns A-E  
9. Now, from the “Financial Aid Grants” page that you ended on, copy all of the student information for the grants that you have just finalized, and paste it into empty space on the far right so it doesn’t interfere with anything. Now, copy all the usernames below the “H3” where it says “Usernames.” Note that sometimes the first username won’t copy properly, so you have to manually add it. You can delete the rest of the data that isn’t for usernames. Now, you have to find the emails that match up with these usernames.  
10. Go back to the main Splash site. Go to “Manage” and then to your program page. Under “Generate Printables,” go to “Arbitrary User List”  
11. Click “Continue to Select set of Contacts” and then “Students who have been granted financial aid.”  
12. Select “ID” “Username” “Full name” and “Email” and generate the list in HTML format  
13. Hit Cntrl “a” to select the whole output and copy it into columns A-E on the spreadsheet. Delete the “Generated for…” text and move all of the data upwards so it looks like this:  
    ![][image9]  
14. Now, besides each username, each email address should have appeared. Check the first input to make sure it is correct.  
15. Copy all the email addresses and paste them into the “BCC.” then address the email to [yalesplash@gmail.com](mailto:yalesplash@gmail.com). You HAVE to do this or else other people can see the email addresses of the other financial aid people.  
16.  The subject should be “Splash Financial Aid Request Approved” and the body should be something like:  
      
    “Hello,  
      
    Your financial aid request for \_\_\_fall or spring\_\_\_\_ Splash \_\_\_year\_\_ has been approved. You will receive full financial aid. We look forward to seeing you at Splash\!  
      
    Best,  
    Avi, Splash Co-Director 2019”

Below you can find the info for generating the PDF’s for Docuprint; after that, you can see a sample DocuPrint request. The cost should be in the ballpark of $530. It is super important that nothing is messed up on the request, so definitely double check it\!

**GENERATE SCHEDULES & NAMETAGS AT THE SAME TIME or there will be extra nametags/extra schedules if you cancel some registrations or whatever**

Student schedules

* On the program dashboard for your program, on the right near the bottom there is a heading “Generate Printables”. One of the quick links there is “Student Schedules.”  
* When you click the link, you’ll get a page to create arbitrary user list; this will select the list of students whose schedules get generated.  
* Choose “students who are enrolled in at least one class” and hit “Continue” to generate the pdf of schedules. (This will take \*a while\*, website is slow.)  
  * We count students as “registered” if they have signed up for at least one class, so this gets you the list of students who have done that.  
  * DO NOT choose the option of “students who have clicked on the ‘Confirm Pre-Registration’ button”; not everyone does the “confirm reg” step and so this list will not get you everyone who is eligible to come to the program.

Student nametags

* I’ve never used firefox (as suggested in the “guide to happy IDs”) so if you use a different browser it should be okay, but if things look wonky then I’d suggest taking another look at those suggestions.  
* Check the option “Students” under ID Type.  
  * You can ignore the “Miscellaneous”, “Number”, and “Title” text boxes since those are just for if you’re doing blank IDs; choosing “Students” will automatically print all of the Student ones and title them “Student”  
* Make sure your program name looks correct, then click “Generate IDs”.  
* Take a quick look through the output to make sure nothing looks wonky then save as a pdf\!

On DocuPrint under “Describe your project,” write something like this and be sure to fill in all the appropriate numbers

We are looking to place a custom order for a student program. We would like 1090 single-sided black and white printed pages which are student schedules for our program. We would then like 1090 student nametags (I've attached a file showing the nametag template) printed onto cardstock. There are 6 nametags to a page, so this would be 182 pages of nametags. We would then like the cardstock nametags to be cut out/separated and stapled to the corresponding student schedule in the bottom corner (i.e. If you had a student, Jack, you would print out his schedule, print out his nametag onto a cardstock page which contains 5 other nametags, cut out his nametag, and staple it to the bottom corner of his schedule (and do that for all 1090 students)). Separate from those 1090 stapled student schedules and nametags, we would like another 1090 pages of handouts printed in black and white double sided (such that the final order would be around 1090 black and white single-sided student schedules which have cardstock nametags stapled to them and another 1090 double-sided pages). The double-sided pages will have the map on one side and the student survey on the other). Both name tags and student schedules should be in the same order (both are alphabetized, and nametags are alphabetized in stacks of 6--i.e. when you cut down all pages to get the nametags, you'll have six alphabetized stacks). That should hopefully make the cutting out/stapling more efficient. We are looking for a price estimate for how much that order would cost. The files are attached and we would be looking to pick the order up before you close on November 13th. If it affects pricing, we are a group of students and also a registered 501(c)3 non-profit. We have an organization credit card so we can pay with that when we come to pick up in the store. Thanks so much\!

### S5.03 Making a Teacher Check-in Spreadsheet {#s5.03-making-a-teacher-check-in-spreadsheet}

Source: In the  “How-To’s” folder  
This is the spreadsheet that will be used to check in teachers on the day of the program. There are a lot of steps to making it correctly, but it’s important that they all get done because teacher check-in can be hectic on the day of the program so doing it correctly now will save hassle and avoid mistakes later.

1. For Sprout: Make a spreadsheet with 3 sheets, one for each day of the program.  
   For Splash: Make a spreadsheet with 6 sheets, one for each block of the program.  
   For both: your spreadsheet should have the following columns: Teacher name, teacher phone number, class location, checked in?, nametag/schedule?, T-shirt?, materials/printables?, adapters, and name. You can copy the overall formatting from a past program’s spreadsheet and change the specific data, just make sure to read through the steps here to avoid repeating past mistakes.  
2. Go to this link: [https://yale.learningu.org/manage/Splash/2019\_Spring/classesbytime](https://yale.learningu.org/manage/Splash/2019_Spring/classesbytime) (also accessible via Manage\>All Printables\>Class Sections sorted by time). This will pull up all the necessary information about the classes to put in the spreadsheet.  
3. Copy the information from the sheet (teacher names, phone numbers, class location) on the website to the relevant sheet on your spreadsheet.  
   1. Alphabetize the list of teachers so they’re easier to find.  
   2. Add conditional formatting so that the row turns green when the teacher is marked as “here”  
4. Check the adapter column against [this list](https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1gQH4NLumeG3TRrMMPj4dGhKUqgsnGcMv9Fgwui6aBYA/edit#gid=0), add/remove adapters as necessary.  
5. **Co-teachers:** It is important to indicate which teachers are co-teaching with someone else, as it is a much bigger deal if a solo teacher is late than if one out of three co-teachers is late. You can put all three co-teachers in the same row of the spreadsheet, or put them in separate rows and color-code the font colors, as long as it is clear to someone looking at the spreadsheet.  
6. Materials requests and printables: If a teacher has materials that we’re providing or printables that we have printed for them, that should go in the “materials/printables?” column. Check the materials spreadsheet for any Splash-provided materials and the gmail for any printables, and mark that accordingly.  
7. Mark anyone who taught the block before as “Taught block before” in the “Here?” column
